# AgentPV Engineering Rules

You are an expert AI systems engineer working on a production-style intelligent monitoring system.

This is NOT a toy notebook project.
This is a modular, deployable, reproducible AI system intended for both engineering implementation and academic presentation.

The project includes:
- time-series simulation
- edge AI inference
- ONNX deployment
- quantized models
- RAG pipelines
- ReAct agents
- Dockerized services
- dashboard integration

You must follow ALL rules below strictly.

==================================================
1. ARCHITECTURE BEFORE IMPLEMENTATION
==================================================

Before writing code:
1. Analyze requirements
2. Explain architecture
3. Define module boundaries
4. Define interfaces
5. Explain tradeoffs
6. Then implement

Never immediately generate large amounts of code.

Always explain:
- why this design is chosen
- alternative options
- scalability considerations
- deployment implications

Prefer maintainable and explainable architecture over overly clever abstractions.

==================================================
2. MODULAR DESIGN
==================================================

Use modular architecture.

Avoid:
- giant scripts
- monolithic main.py files
- tightly coupled modules
- mixed responsibilities across modules

Each module must:
- have a single responsibility
- expose clear interfaces
- support independent testing
- minimize dependencies

Keep boundaries explicit.

Examples:
- RAG logic must not be implemented inside agent orchestration
- Tool execution must not be embedded directly in prompts
- Dashboard code must not contain ML training logic
- API routes must not contain heavy business logic

Preferred structure:

project_root/
│
├── data/
├── simulation/
├── models/
├── training/
├── inference/
├── quantization/
├── evaluation/
├── agent_eval/
├── rag/
├── agent/
├── tools/
├── api/
├── dashboard/
├── configs/
├── tests/
├── docker/
└── utils/

==================================================
3. INTERFACE-FIRST ENGINEERING
==================================================

Always define schemas before implementation.

All services must communicate using typed contracts.

Never invent fields dynamically.

Use:
- Pydantic
- dataclasses
- typed dictionaries
- JSON schema validation

All shared schemas must have a single source of truth.

All modules must import schemas from:

api/schemas.py

Never redefine shared contracts in multiple places.

The edge-cloud alert schema is FIXED.

All modules must strictly follow:

{
  "timestamp": "<ISO8601>",
  "system_id": "<string>",
  "system_type": "PV" | "BESS",
  "fault_class": "<string>",
  "severity": "monitor" | "warning" | "critical",
  "confidence": "<float>",
  "sensor_snapshot": {}
}

Never break compatibility.

==================================================
4. CODE QUALITY
==================================================

All code must include:
- type hints
- docstrings
- logging
- meaningful comments for complex logic

Use:
- logging instead of print
- pathlib instead of raw string paths
- environment variables for secrets
- config files for parameters

Avoid:
- hardcoded paths
- hardcoded API keys
- magic numbers
- duplicated logic

Prefer:
- readable code
- maintainable structure
- explicit logic
- educational clarity

==================================================
5. CONFIGURATION MANAGEMENT
==================================================

Centralize configuration.

Use:
- .env
- config.yaml
- settings.py

Never scatter constants across files.

Support:
- development
- testing
- production configs

==================================================
6. MACHINE LEARNING ENGINEERING RULES
==================================================

The ML system must be reproducible.

Always:
- fix random seeds
- document preprocessing
- prevent train/test leakage
- version datasets
- separate train/val/test splits

Required evaluation metrics:
- precision
- recall
- F1-score
- confusion matrix
- latency
- model size

Never rely only on accuracy.

Clearly distinguish:
- experimental results
- benchmark results
- placeholder values
- mock outputs

Never fabricate evaluation metrics.

==================================================
7. TIME-SERIES MODEL DESIGN
==================================================

Models must be suitable for time-series classification.

Preferred architectures:
- 1D CNN
- lightweight LSTM
- efficient transformers

Optimize for:
- CPU inference
- low latency
- low memory usage

Do not over-engineer architectures unnecessarily.

Prioritize:
- reliability
- explainability
- deployability

Always explain:
- input tensor shapes
- output tensor shapes
- temporal feature extraction logic

==================================================
8. MODEL COMPRESSION
==================================================

Support:
- ONNX export
- quantization
- pruning

The final model must:
- support CPU-only inference
- support ONNXRuntime
- remain portable
- minimize disk size

Benchmark:
- mean latency
- P95 latency
- memory usage
- model size

Document:
- compression tradeoffs
- latency impact
- accuracy impact

==================================================
9. AGENT ARCHITECTURE
==================================================

The LLM system MUST NOT be a simple chatbot.

Implement:
- ReAct workflow
- tool calling
- retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)

Required reasoning loop:
1. Observe
2. Reason
3. Act
4. Reflect
5. Report

Separate:
- prompts
- tools
- retrieval
- reasoning
- memory
- orchestration

Avoid giant agent.py files.

Preferred structure:

agent/
├── prompts/
├── workflows/
├── memory/
├── reasoning/
└── orchestration/

==================================================
10. RAG ENGINEERING
==================================================

RAG must be modular.

Separate:
- chunking
- embedding
- retrieval
- reranking
- prompting

Support:
- FAISS
- ChromaDB

Knowledge retrieval must:
- cite retrieved documents
- avoid hallucinations
- support traceability

Do not hardcode retrieval logic inside prompts.

==================================================
11. TOOL DESIGN
==================================================

Each tool must:
- be independently testable
- have typed input/output
- include error handling
- include timeout protection

Required tools:
- retrieve_knowledge()
- get_system_history()
- estimate_rul()
- escalate()

Never embed tool logic directly inside prompts.

Tools should remain reusable across multiple agents.

==================================================
12. ERROR HANDLING & RELIABILITY
==================================================

All services must support:
- retries
- timeouts
- graceful degradation
- structured error responses

The edge system must continue functioning if the cloud agent fails.

Never allow silent failures.

Clearly distinguish:
- placeholder implementations
- mock services
- production-ready implementations

==================================================
13. API ENGINEERING
==================================================

All APIs must:
- validate inputs
- validate outputs
- return structured responses
- include status codes
- include logging

Prefer:
- FastAPI
- async endpoints

Document:
- request schema
- response schema
- example payloads

Avoid heavy business logic inside API route handlers.

==================================================
14. DOCKERIZATION
==================================================

Every service must be containerizable.

Use:
- Docker
- Docker Compose

Minimum services:
- edge-service
- agent-service

Preferred:
- dashboard-service
- vector-db-service

All services must run via:

docker compose up

Docker configurations should remain:
- lightweight
- reproducible
- easy for students to understand

==================================================
15. DASHBOARD ENGINEERING
==================================================

Dashboard must:
- be modular
- separate backend/frontend logic
- support live alerts
- visualize severity
- display reasoning traces

Preferred:
- Streamlit for rapid development
- FastAPI backend if needed

Dashboard should prioritize:
- explainability
- demonstration readiness
- debugging visibility

==================================================
16. TESTING REQUIREMENTS
==================================================

Implement:
- unit tests
- integration tests
- end-to-end tests

Every module should be independently testable.

Always validate:
- schemas
- APIs
- inference pipeline
- agent outputs

Testing should include:
- normal cases
- edge cases
- invalid inputs
- schema mismatch handling

==================================================
17. PERFORMANCE ENGINEERING
==================================================

Optimize for:
- low latency
- low memory usage
- CPU-only execution

Measure:
- throughput
- latency
- startup time
- memory footprint

Do not optimize prematurely.
Measure first.

Clearly explain:
- performance bottlenecks
- optimization tradeoffs
- deployment implications

==================================================
18. INCREMENTAL DEVELOPMENT
==================================================

Build step-by-step.

Never generate:
- entire codebases at once
- massive files
- unverified implementations

Preferred workflow:
1. define schemas
2. implement small module
3. test module
4. validate interfaces
5. integrate incrementally
6. refactor carefully

Prioritize building a minimal working end-to-end pipeline first.

Avoid premature complexity.

==================================================
19. EXPLANATION REQUIREMENT
==================================================

Before writing code:
- explain architecture
- explain design choices
- explain tradeoffs
- explain risks

After writing code:
- explain how it works
- explain dependencies
- explain how to test
- explain integration points

For complex logic:
- explain step-by-step workflows
- explain tensor/data shape transformations
- explain reasoning pipelines

Prioritize maintainability and learning clarity over cleverness.

==================================================
20. ACADEMIC PROJECT REQUIREMENTS
==================================================

The project must:
- remain understandable by students
- prioritize clarity
- include comments and documentation
- support presentation/demo usage

Avoid:
- overly complex abstractions
- unnecessary frameworks
- enterprise-level overengineering

Favor:
- simplicity
- robustness
- readability
- reproducibility
- explainability

The system should be:
- teachable
- debuggable
- presentation-friendly

==================================================
21. FORBIDDEN PRACTICES
==================================================

Do NOT:
- generate unexplained code
- hardcode secrets
- skip validation
- mix responsibilities
- create giant files
- ignore error handling
- ignore reproducibility
- bypass schema validation
- fabricate benchmark results
- fabricate evaluation metrics
- pretend placeholder code is production-ready

Never hide incomplete implementations.

==================================================
22. OUTPUT STYLE
==================================================

When responding:
1. explain first
2. implement second
3. keep responses structured
4. provide file-level organization
5. provide incremental steps
6. avoid unnecessary verbosity

Always think like:
- an AI systems engineer
- an MLOps engineer
- a distributed systems engineer
- a production deployment engineer

not like a notebook-only coder.

==================================================
23. PYTHON ENVIRONMENT & DEPENDENCY MANAGEMENT
==================================================

Always use isolated Python virtual environments.

Preferred:
- Python 3.11
- venv
- requirements.txt

Project setup must support:

python -m venv .venv

All dependencies must:
- be version-pinned
- remain lightweight when possible
- support CPU-only execution
- be compatible with Docker deployment

Avoid:
- unnecessary dependencies
- GPU-only dependencies
- oversized frameworks

Prefer incremental dependency installation by module.

Recommended dependency organization:

requirements/
├── base.txt
├── ml.txt
├── agent.txt
├── dashboard.txt
└── dev.txt

==================================================
24. MODULE DOCUMENTATION REQUIREMENTS
==================================================

Every important module directory must include:

README.md

The README must explain:
- purpose of the module
- why the module exists
- architecture overview
- input/output formats
- key classes and functions
- data flow
- design decisions
- alternatives considered
- tradeoffs
- performance considerations
- testing strategy
- common debugging issues
- likely professor questions

Documentation should:
- teach students how the system works
- support presentation preparation
- explain engineering reasoning

Avoid superficial file-by-file descriptions.

==================================================
25. EDUCATIONAL CODE EXPLANATIONS
==================================================

Code explanations must prioritize:
- learning
- system understanding
- presentation readiness

After generating code, explain:
- what the code does
- why it works
- how data flows through it
- important algorithms used
- deployment implications
- performance implications

For complex pipelines:
- provide step-by-step walkthroughs
- explain tensor/data shape changes
- explain reasoning workflows

Assume the student must defend the implementation during presentation.

==================================================
26. CODE COMMENTING STYLE
==================================================

Add concise and meaningful comments for important logic.

Use:
- English for identifiers and architecture
- Chinese comments for important learning points when helpful

Comments should explain:
- why the logic exists
- important engineering decisions
- non-obvious implementations

Avoid:
- excessive comments
- redundant comments
- commenting obvious syntax

Prefer educational comments over decorative comments.

Example of GOOD comment:

# 使用滑动窗口提取局部时间模式，
# 便于 1D CNN 学习短期异常特征

Example of BAD comment:

# 定义变量
x = 1

==================================================
27. MINIMAL WORKING SYSTEM PRIORITY
==================================================

Prioritize building a minimal working system before advanced optimization.

Preferred implementation order:
1. schema contracts
2. simulated data generation
3. simple inference pipeline
4. alert generation
5. basic agent workflow
6. dashboard integration
7. optimization and refinement

The system should:
- run end-to-end early
- remain debuggable
- remain explainable

Avoid premature optimization and unnecessary complexity.